**Influence functions** (Koh & Liang, 2017) estimate the effect of removing a training point on model parameters (and hence on predictions) without retraining. The influence of $z = (x,y) \in \mathcal{D}$ on model parameters: $\mathcal{I}_{	ext{params}}(z) = H^{-1} 
abla_	heta \mathcal{L}(	heta^*, z)$. The influence on the loss at a test point $z_{	ext{test}}$: $\mathcal{I}_{	ext{loss}}(z, z_{	ext{test}}) = -
abla_	heta \mathcal{L}(	heta^*, z_{	ext{test}})^T H^{-1} 
abla_	heta \mathcal{L}(	heta^*, z)$. This can be computed without the Hessian inverse explicitly via **conjugate gradient** solving $H v = 
abla_	heta \mathcal{L}(z_{	ext{test}})$ for $v = H^{-1} 
abla_	heta \mathcal{L}(z_{	ext{test}})$. Influence functions identify **which training examples most influenced a specific prediction** — enabling data debugging, poison detection, and attribution. For unlearning: update $	heta' = 	heta - \eta \mathcal{I}_{	ext{params}}(\mathcal{D}_f)$ (one Newton step).
